  "local_port": 48340,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights at an airport, especially one as large as Paris Charles de Gaulle (CDG) or Paris Orly (ORY), can seem daunting, but with a bit of preparation, it can be a smooth process. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you navigate your connection in Paris:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Check Your Flight Details**\n   - **Airline(s):** Are both flights with the same airline or partner airlines (e.g., Air France/KLM)? If so, your luggage might be checked through to Prague.\n   - **Terminal/Layout:** Paris CDG has multiple terminals (1, 2A, 2B, 2C, 2D, 2E, 2F, 3). Orly has two main terminals (West and South). Check your flight details to know which terminals you\u2019ll be arriving at and departing from.\n   - **Layover Time:** Ensure you have enough time between flights (at least 1.5\u20132 hours for domestic/international connections and 2+ hours for security/customs if applicable).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Luggage Arrangements**\n   - If you\u2019ve booked both flights on a single ticket and with the same airline, your luggage will likely be checked through to Prague. Confirm this at check-in.\n   - If you\u2019re flying with different airlines or separate tickets, you\u2019ll need to collect your luggage in Paris and check it in again for your flight to Prague.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Arrival in Paris**\n   - Follow signs for **\"Connections\"** (Correspondances in French) if your luggage is checked through and you\u2019re on a single ticket.\n   - If you need to collect your luggage and check in again, follow signs to **\"Baggage Claim\"** (Livraison des bagages) and then proceed to the check-in counter for your next flight.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Security and Customs**\n   - If you\u2019re arriving from a non-Schengen country and flying to Prague (a Schengen country), you\u2019ll go through passport control in Paris.\n   - You may also need to go through security screening again, depending on the terminal.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Navigating the Airport**\n   - Use airport maps or signs to find your next gate. Both CDG and Orly have clear signage in English and French.\n   - If terminals are far apart, use the free shuttle buses (navettes) at CDG or the Orlyval train at Orly.\n   - Check flight information screens for updates on your flight\u2019s gate and boarding time.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Time Management**\n   - Don\u2019t linger\u2014Paris airports are large, and it can take time to get from one terminal to another.\n   - Allow extra time if you need to go through passport control or security.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Ask for Help**\n   - If you\u2019re unsure, ask airport staff or look for information desks. Most staff speak English.\n   - Use apps like the Paris Airport app or your airline\u2019s app for real-time updates.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Boarding Your Flight to Prague**\n   - Arrive at your gate at least 30\u201345 minutes before departure.\n   - Have your passport and boarding pass ready for inspection.\n\n---\n\n### Tips for a Smooth Connection:\n   - Wear comfortable shoes for walking.\n   - Keep essentials (passport, boarding pass, etc.) in your carry-on.\n   - Stay updated on any flight delays or gate changes.\n\n---\n\nSafe travels, and enjoy your time in Prague! \ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddff\u2708\ufe0f",
  "temperature": 1.0,
